  "analysis": {
    "lecture_question": "How can phenomenological personality psychology investigate structures of subjectivity and lived experience through the first-person perspective?",
    "central_learning_problem": "Students accustomed to viewing personality as a set of static internal traits or measurable variables must shift to understanding it as a dynamic, situated meaning-making process. The challenge lies in grasping how rigorous scientific inquiry can be conducted from a first-person perspective using concepts like intentionality, epoché, and the pre-reflective body, without reducing the lived experience (Lifeworld) to mere objective data.",
